docs.abstract: For years, the company has tried to change the perception that its software was vulnerable to hackers. A global cyberattack renewed those issues.

docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — When malicious software first became a serious problem on the internet about 15 years ago, most people agreed that the biggest villain, after the authors of the damaging code, was Microsoft.

headline.main: In Ransomware Attack, Where Does Microsoft’s Responsibility Lie?
headline.print_headline: Ransomware Attack Refocuses a Light on an Old Problem for Microsoft: Security

docs.abstract: Our software systems are like unstable cities built on swamps. We could fix them if the industry and the government took decisive action.
docs.snippet: Our software systems are like unstable cities built on swamps. We could fix them if the industry and the government took decisive action.
docs.lead_paragraph: The path to a global outbreak on Friday of a ransom-demanding computer software (“ransomware”) that crippled hospitals in Britain — forcing the rerouting of ambulances, delays in surgeries and the shutdown of diagnostic equipment — started, as it often does, with a defect in software, a bug. This is perhaps the first salvo of a global crisis that has been brewing for decades. Fixing this is possible, but it will be expensive and require a complete overhaul of how technology companies, governments and institutions operate and handle software. The alternative should be unthinkable.

headline.main: The World Is Getting Hacked. Why Don’t We Do More to Stop It?
headline.print_headline: Why the World Is Getting Hacked

docs.abstract: Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Facebook and Google dominate our day-to-day activities. Imagining being forced to give up some of them could lead to hard choices.
docs.snippet: Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Facebook and Google dominate our day-to-day activities. Imagining being forced to give up some of them could lead to hard choices.
docs.lead_paragraph: A few weeks ago, I bought a new television. When the whole process was over, I realized something incredible: To navigate all of the niggling details surrounding this one commercial transaction — figuring out what to buy, which accessories I needed, how and where to install it, and whom to hire to do so — I had dealt with only a single ubiquitous corporation: Amazon.

headline.main: Tech’s Frightful Five: They’ve Got Us
headline.print_headline: Which Tech Overlords Can You Live Without?
